Project Problem Statement - Neural Networks - Bank Churn Prediction¶

Objective:¶

Given a Bank customer, build a neural network-based classifier that can determine whether they will leave or not in the next 6 months.

Context:¶

Businesses like banks that provide service have to worry about the problem of 'Churn' i.e. customers leaving and joining another service provider. It is important to understand which aspects of the service influence a customer's decision in this regard. Management can concentrate efforts on the improvement of service, keeping in mind these priorities.

Data Description:¶

The case study is from an open-source dataset from Kaggle. The dataset contains 10,000 sample points with 14 distinct features such as CustomerId, CreditScore, Geography, Gender, Age, Tenure, Balance, etc. Link to the Kaggle project site:https://www.kaggle.com/barelydedicated/bank-customer-churn-modeling

Data Dictionary:¶

  • RowNumber: Row number.
  • CustomerId: Unique identification key for different customers.
  • Surname: Surname of the customer
  • Credit Score: Credit score is a measure of an individual's ability to pay back the borrowed amount. It is the numerical representation of their creditworthiness. A credit score is a 3-digit number that falls in the range of 300-900, 900 being the highest.
  • Geography: The country to which the customer belongs.
  • Gender: The gender of the customer.
  • Age: Age of the customer.
  • Tenure: The period of time a customer has been associated with the bank.
  • Balance: The account balance (the amount of money deposited in the bank account) of the customer.
  • NumOfProducts: How many accounts, bank account affiliated products the person has.
  • HasCrCard: Does the customer have a credit card through the bank?
  • IsActiveMember: Subjective, but for the concept
  • EstimatedSalary: Estimated salary of the customer.
  • Exited: Did they leave the bank after all?

Insights

  • RowNumber and CustomerID - has unique records - which not a potential preditive feature, can be droped.
  • CreditScore - starts from 350 to 850 max - with mean 650.53 and median 652.00 - mean and median is much closure could be normally distributed.
  • Age - included from 18 - 92, mean 38.92 and meadian 37 - mean and median is much closure could be normally distributed.
  • Tensure - starts from 0 - 10, mean = 5.01 and meadian 5.00 - mean and median is much closure could be normally distributed.
  • Balance - stars from 0 - 250898.09 max - mean = 76485.89 and median = 97198.54. 25% of the customers have 0 balance - huge difference between mean and median could have highly dispersion. Median > mean definately negatively skewed - required normalization or standardisation.
  • NumOfProduct - 1-4, mean 1.53 and median 1 - meaning more than 50% customers hold only 1 product - Positively skewed
  • HasCrCard - binary 0 and 1 , mean 0.71 and median 1 - meaning more than 25% has no credit card whereas 75% has credit card - Negatively skewed
  • IsActiveMember - binary 0 and 1 , mean 0.52 and median 1 - meaning more than 25% has not an active customers whereas 75% active - Negatively skewed
  • EstimatedSalary - 11.58 - 199992.48, mean = 100090.24 and median = 100193.92 - mean and median very close could be normally distributed - data required treatment.
  • Exited - Dependent variable - binary 0 and 1 - 75% customers Churn and 25% not Churn - data not balanced and require special treatments.

Normalization¶

In [31]:
# data normalization with sklearn
from sklearn.preprocessing import MinMaxScaler, StandardScaler, MaxAbsScaler
from sklearn import preprocessing

# fit scaler on training data
norm = MinMaxScaler().fit(X_train)

# transform training data
X_train_norm = norm.transform(X_train)

# transform testing dataabs
X_test_norm = norm.transform(X_test)

Insights

  • Normalization is good to use when you know that the distribution of your data does not follow a Normal distribution.
  • This can be useful in algorithms that do not assume any distribution of the data like K-Nearest Neighbors and Neural Networks.
  • Standardization, on the other hand, can be helpful in cases where the data follows a Gaussian distribution.
  • Unlike normalization, standardization does not have a bounding range. So, even if you have outliers in your data, they will not be affected by standardization.
  • We have tried both Normalization and Standardization which MinMaxScaler gives higher scores so considering it
  • MinMaxScaler = 86.73
  • StandardScaler = 85.23
  • MaxAbsScaler = 83.79

Hyperparameters Tuning¶

  • we found the model accuracy is about 0.863 by using 'adams' by Adamax is 0.861 and by using 'rmsprop' to 0.849.
  • 'adam' optimizer gives the highiest score so we use it.
  • eopchs = [50,100,200,500,1000] - 1000 shows higher accuracy - it was observed that it the accuracy score initially increase and then its slowly decrease and then its started optimzing - that's the beauty of the Neural Networks - Neurons learn from the forward propogation and backward learning. So 1000 eopchs will be the optimal
  • batches [50,100, 500, 1000] - 10000/1000 = 10 batches which is optimal.
  • loss_functions = we are using binary output 0 or 1 so binary_crossentropy is optimal

Conclusion¶

  • We implemented the Deep Neural Network for predicting customer churn for the bank customers. The aim of the show the study is to identify the features of churners. Demographic variables (e.g., age, gender, balance, expected salary, geography, gender, active cutomers, has credit card) were extracted from the banks database.
  • Forward selection and backward elimination methods were applied for feature subset selection after data massaging.

  • The results of the DNN model predicts the churners:

  • AGE - people less than 40 shows higher chrun which is clearly visible using the distplot - Age is important feature to predict chrun.

  • Balance - Customers has 0 balance shows higher chrun which is clearly visible using the distplot - Balance is important feature to predict chrun.
  • NumOfProduct - Customers has 1 & 2 shows higher chrun comparing greater than 2 products - NumOfProduct is important feature to predict chrun.
  • HasCrCard - Customers has credit cards shows higher churn comparing others - HasCrCard is important feature to predict chrun
  • IsActiveMember - Active members shows higher chrun obviously Inactive customers idle - IsActiveMember is important feature to predict churn.

Busines Insights and Recomendations:¶

  • It is expected that, with a better understanding of the features of churners, bank managers can consider some strategies to prevent churn. These strategies should be used for customers whose features are growing more similar to the churner groups identified above. These strategies can include providing required facilities, improving the quality of services, identifying the needs of different groups, and increasing customer responsiveness.

  • Age - less than 40-60 has more churn - need special promotions to attract and retain customers

  • Balance - 0 balance customers shows higher chruns need special analysis to understand these cluster to come up with new special promotions
  • NumOfProducts - Customers has 2> shows higher chrun comparing less than 2 products - existing customers should get special promotions and higher interest to attract them to undertake new product - study also shows that customers have more products goes less chrns.
  • NumOfProduct = 4 - all the customers who has 4 products all left the bank. Bank need to investigate the 4 product and need to improve.
  • Customers has credit cards shows higher churs - credit card shows higher churn. So credit card segment should have been introduced more promotions to retain customers.
